cultural experience that represents the women of the First Nations, a realistic picture will have many facets. Accordingly, the authors in Women of the First Nations include Native and non-Native scholars, feminists, and activists from across Canada.Their work examines various aspects of Aboriginal women's lives from a variety of theoretical and personal perspectives. They discuss standard media representations, as well as historical and current realities. They bring new perspectives to discussions on Aboriginal art, literature, historical, and cultural contributions, and they offer diverse viewpoints on present economic, environmental, and political issues.This collection counters the marginalization and silencing of First Nations women's voices and reflects the power, strength, and wisdom inherent in their lives.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / Native American Studies.2bisacsh1 aArmstrong, Jeannette, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBastien, Betty, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlythe, Jennifer, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrown, Rosemary, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarter, Sarah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChuchryk, Patricia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChuchryk, Patricia, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aEmberley, Julia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFiske, Jo-Anne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLaRocque, Emma, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aM\x27Closkey, Kathy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabula